{{Orphan|date=September 2015}}
{{Infobox court case | name = Tri-Star Customs and Forwarding Ltd v Denning | court = [[Court of Appeal of New Zealand]] | date_filed = | image = Coat of arms of New Zealand.svg | date decided = 2 July 1998 | full name = Tri-Star Customs and Forwarding Ltd v Denning | citations = [1999] 1 NZLR 33 | judges = [[Ivor Richardson|Richardson J]], [[John Henry (judge)|Henry J]], [[Ted Thomas (judge)|Thomas J]], [[Kenneth Keith|Keith J]], [[Andrew Tipping|Tipping J]] | prior actions = | subsequent actions = | opinions = | transcripts = | Keywords = }} '''Tri-Star Customs and Forwarding Ltd v Denning''' [1999] 1 NZLR 33 is a cited case in New Zealand regarding unilateral mistakes under the [[Contractual Mistakes Act 1977]].<ref name="Chetwin, Graw, Tiong">{{cite book |title=An introduction to the Law of Contract in New Zealand |edition=4th |last1=Chetwin |first1=Maree |last2=Graw |first2=Stephen |last3=Tiong |first3=Raymond |publisher=Thomson Brookers |ISBN=0-86472-555-8 |year=2006 |page=280 - 281}}</ref><ref name="Walker">{{cite book |title=Butterworths Student Companion Contract |edition=4th |last1=Walker |first1=Campbell |publisher=LexisNexis |ISBN=0-408-71770-X|year=2004 |page=117-118}}</ref>
==Background== The Dennings leased a commercial building to Tristar. A condition of the lease agreement, gave Tristar the right to purchase the building for $720,000. An option that Tristar later accepted.
However, whilst the lease agreement clearly stated that the rentals were GST exclusive, the purchase price of $720,000 was silent regarding whether it exclusive or inclusive of GST.
This was unfortunate for the Dennings, as under NZ tax law, it was deemed that it was GST inclusive, although they successfully obtained relief in the High Court.
Tristar appealed.
==Held== A [[bench of five]] of the Court Appeal ruled that the Contractual Mistakes Act 1977 requires that Tristar had actual knowledge of the mistake at the time, and not merely "ought to of known" of the mistake as was the old common law standard. Henry J stated "It may of course be proper for the Court to infer actual knowledge from proved circumstances, even if the person in question denies having that knowledge".
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:Court of Appeal of New Zealand cases]] [[Category:New Zealand contract case law]] [[Category:1998 in New Zealand law]] [[Category:1998 in case law]]
{{NewZealand-case-law-stub}}

{{Italic title}}
'''''Working Key to the Genera of North American Algae''''' is an influential early technical reference book on identification of [[algae]] in [[North America]].

It was written by [[Frank Shipley Collins]], and published in 1918.<ref name=MAB>Makers of American Botany, [[Harry Baker Humphrey]], Ronald Press Company, Library of Congress Card Number 61-18435</ref>{{rp|56}}

